item.description:
We always eager to understand &ldquo;when it can be achieved&rdquo; or &ldquo;when it will happen.&rdquo;
Eliot gives a different answer in &ldquo;East Coker&rdquo;:
&ldquo;I Said to My Soul, Be Still&rdquo; I said to my soul, be still, and wait without hope
For hope would be hope for the wrong thing;
wait without love,
For love would be love of the wrong thing;
there is yet faith,
But the faith and the love and the hope are all in the waiting.
